<div class="post">
  <h2><a href="/articles/2011/10/07/arrrrcamp-presentation-design-workflows-for-rails/">ArrrrCamp Presentation: Design Workflows for Rails</a></h2>
  <p class="info">by <a href="/about/">John W. Long</a> on October  7, 2011</p>
  <noscript><a href="/articles/2011/10/07/arrrrcamp-presentation-design-workflows-for-rails/"><img src="https://speakerd.s3.amazonaws.com/presentations/4e8eccb395051c0054009092/preview_slide_0.jpg" alt="Title Slide" /></a></noscript><script src="http://speakerdeck.com/embed/4e8eccb395051c0054009092.js"></script><p>I&#8217;m at <a href="http://arrrrcamp.be">ArrrrCamp</a> in Belgium for the weekend and just gave a presentation on &#8220;Design Workflows for Rails.&#8221;</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s the abstract:</p>
<p>&#8220;We&#8217;ve come a long way since the early days of Rails. And the entire Rails system, while much more robust, can be intimidating and downright frustrating for designers. In this talk we&#8217;ll discuss a couple of different strategies for integrating designers into your team and what you can do to optimize your current designer/developer workflow. We&#8217;ll be discussing a couple of tools that can assist you in this (including John&#8217;s very own <a href="http://get-serve.com">Serve</a> project). Along the way we will be talking a lot about the value of taking a design-first approach to software development and you will walk away with a number of practical approaches that you can apply to your current project even if you aren&#8217;t working with a designer.&#8221;</p>
  
</div>

<div class="post">
  <h2><a href="/articles/2011/07/13/serve-1-5-delicious-erb-haml-and-sass/">Serve 1.5 – Utterly Delicious ERB, Haml and Sass</a></h2>
  <p class="info">by <a href="/about/">John W. Long</a> on July 13, 2011</p>
  <p><a href="/articles/2011/07/13/serve-1-5-delicious-erb-haml-and-sass/"><img src="/page_attachments/0000/0050/serve.png" /></a></p>
<p>If you&#8217;ve been following my <a href="http://twitter.com/johnwlong">Twitter stream</a> at all during the last month, you know that I&#8217;ve been hard at work on a project I like to call, Serve. Serve is an open source project that makes it easy to build websites with <span class="caps">HTML</span>, <span class="caps">ERB</span>, Haml + Sass.</p>
<p>I do a lot of <span class="caps">HTML</span> prototyping for Web applications. I also build a lot of brochure websites for said applications. Serve makes it easy for me to use the tools that I&#8217;ve grown to love while working with Ruby on Rails projects (<span class="caps">ERB</span> + Sass) to construct basic websites.</p>
<p>Serve is modeled a lot on Rails. If you&#8217;re a Rails programmer, you could call it just the Views part of the Rails <acronym title="Model, View, Controller"><span class="caps">MVC</span></acronym>. Serve is built with Rack and Tilt, so it&#8217;s easy to use and deploy on your favorite Ruby platforms. As of 1.5 you can also export your sites as plain <span class="caps">HTML</span> if your Web host doesn&#8217;t support Ruby.</p>
<p>So how&#8217;s it work? Throw your <span class="caps">ERB</span>, Haml, and Sass in a directory, <kbd>cd</kbd> to it on the command prompt, and type:</p>
<pre><code>serve</code></pre>
<p>Then browse over to http://localhost:4000 and view your website there. It&#8217;s that simple.</p>
<p>You can learn more about Serve on it&#8217;s <a href="http://get-serve.com">brand-spanking new website</a>. (Serve&#8217;s new website is actually made with Serve. How meta!)</p>
<p>So let&#8217;s dive into some of my favorite things about 1.5.</p>
  <p class="more"><a href="/articles/2011/07/13/serve-1-5-delicious-erb-haml-and-sass/#extended">Continue Reading</a></p>
</div>

<div class="post">
  <h2><a href="/articles/2011/04/04/simple-site-search/">Simple Site Search</a></h2>
  <p class="info">by <a href="/about/">John W. Long</a> on April  4, 2011</p>
  <p>I just added simple search to this site for my blog posts with the following code:</p>

<pre class="code html-code"><code>&lt;form action="http://google.com/search" method="get"&gt;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;div&gt;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;input type="search" name="q" placeholder="Search" results="0" /&gt;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;input type="hidden" name="q" value="site:wiseheartdesign.com" /&gt;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;<br>&lt;/form&gt;</code></pre>

<p>This will create a working search input that looks like this:</p>

<form action="http://google.com/search" method="get">
<div style="background: #white; border: 4px solid #f7f6f2; border-radius: 3px; -webkit-box-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.0976562) 2px 2px 3px 0px; padding: 1em; margin: 1em 0">
<input type="search" name="q" placeholder="Search" results="0" style="font-size: 16px">
<input type="hidden" name="q" value="site:wiseheartdesign.com">
</div>
</form>

<p>The code above leverages a number of little known facts about <span class="caps">HTML</span> forms and Google:</p>

<ul>
<li>I’ve used two input elements to construct the query for Google. One is an HTML5 search input and the other is a hidden input element. But here’s the kicker: <strong>they both use the same name</strong> — in this case <code>q</code>. This will produce a query string that looks like this: <code>q=test&amp;q=...</code>. Note the presence of two <code>q</code> parameters. Google combines both parameters to create the complete search query.</li>
<li>The hidden input element has a value of <code>site:wiseheartdesign.com</code> which appends this to the end of the normal search string. Google uses this limit a search to a given website.</li>
<li>To cause the form to submit to Google, I’ve set the “action” attribute on the form to <code>http://google.com/search</code>. The “action” attribute can be a full <span class="caps">URL</span> to another site. It doesn’t have to refer to a <span class="caps">URL</span> on your own site.</li>
</ul>

  
</div>

